ce:section.ce:para:
To explore the promoting mechanism of the BNF process, we sequenced the genome to investigate whether GQDs affected the transcription of A. vinelandii genes. The up-regulated expression of the DEGs of A. vinelandii was enhanced by GQDs at concentrations of 0.5, 1, and 5 mg/L, and the up-regulation of gene expression was concentration-dependent (Fig. 5
                        ). These genes were screened for gene clusters associated with carbohydrate metabolism, lipid metabolism, energy metabolism, and nitrogen fixation expression. These results were well corresponded with the observations of a stimulation effect in metabolic rate and electron transport activity. The regulation of genes associated with carbohydrate metabolism plays a direct role in the biological process of nitrogen fixation [57]. The expression of these genes (pgi: 199 %, zwf: 261 %, pyk: 208 %, rfbA: 506 %, galE: 1337 %, mltG: 600 %, lpxK: 1515 %) showed an upregulation trend when the concentration of GQDs was 1 mg/L (Fig. 6
                        A). The presence of GQDs also upregulated genes related to lipid metabolism, which is responsible for the provision of energy for the process of biological nitrogen fixation [58]. The expression of lipid metabolism related genes (ugpC: 115 %, plsY: 288 %, glpD: 910 %, yegS: 351 %, lpxO: 414 %, lpxB: 520 %, waaA: 661 %) showed significant upregulation, particularly at a concentration of 1 mg/L (Fig. 6B). The upregulation of energy metabolism related genes (atpA: 245 %, atpB: 232 %, atpD: 209 %, atpE: 244 %, clpA: 172 %, clpB: 431 %, clpS: 125 %, clpX: 222 %, mgtA: 317 %) further confirmed that GQDs enhanced biological nitrogen fixation by stimulating cellular metabolism (Fig. 6C). The nitrogenase enzyme, as an essential component of biological nitrogen fixation, plays a pivotal role in facilitating this intricate process [45,59]. The nitrogenase genes were significantly stimulated by GQDs at all concentrations (Fig. 6D). Especially, the greatest change of V-Fe nitrogenase genes and Fe-Fe nitrogenase occurred at 1 mg/L group (vnfK: 2245 %, vnfD: 793 %, and vnfG:1782 %, anfK: 1945 %, anfD: 2009 %, and anfG:983 %). These results demonstrated that the utilization of GQDs significantly induced the upregulation of gene clusters, and supported that GQDs at 1 mg/L significantly stimulated the nitrogen fixing activity by influencing the genes encoding V-Fe and Fe-Fe nitrogenase.
